🧭 Project Overview

In this project, we use Terraform to provision an AWS Elastic IP (EIP), which is a static public IPv4 address that can be attached to cloud resources such as EC2 instances.

Unlike normal public IPs, Elastic IPs remain persistent even if the instance is stopped or restarted, making them essential for stable public-facing applications.

🎯 Objective
Create an Elastic IP using Terraform
Understand static vs dynamic public IP addressing
Learn how AWS manages public connectivity
Understand use cases for fixed IP assignment in cloud infrastructure

🧰 Technologies Used
Technology	Purpose
Terraform	Infrastructure as Code (IaC)
AWS EC2	Compute service
AWS Elastic IP	Static public IPv4 address
AWS	Cloud platform

📌 Concept Explanation

An Elastic IP (EIP) is a static IPv4 address provided by AWS that can be associated with:

EC2 instances
Network interfaces
NAT Gateways
Key characteristics:
Persistent (does not change when instance restarts)
Manually allocated and released
Can be reassigned to different resources
Elastic IP vs Normal Public IP
Feature	Public IP	Elastic IP
Persistence	Temporary	Persistent
Change on restart	Yes	No
Reassignment	No	Yes
Use case	Short-lived instances	Production workloads
